YELLOW FEVER - AFRICA (01): SUDAN (DARFUR)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 3 Jan 2013
Source: All Africa [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201301040025.html


The vaccination campaign against yellow fever was launched in Umm Dukhum locality, Central Darfur, on Tuesday, 1 Jan [2013], the state's health minister told Radio Dabanga. Issa Mohamed Moussa Yousef said the operation will be completed on 12 Jan [2013] and that 130 000 people would be targeted.

He also said the ministry allocated 3 medical teams to cover the locality and to temporarily cover the state's borders and public roads. In addition, he continued, mobile teams will be responsible for nomads and other teams will be operating in health centers and hospitals of the locality.

Yousef said his ministry took certain precautions, in coordination with the World Health Organisation, concerning the status of Umm Dukhum. The locality lies in the border area between Chad, Central African Republic and Sudan.

The minister appealed to all citizens of Umm Dukhum, especially to native administrators, to immediately notify authorities if new cases of yellow fever emerge.

He also asked that citizens inform authorities if certain areas of Umm Dukhum are not covered by the vaccination campaign.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Given the relative proximity of Umm Dukhum to the Chad and Central African Republic borders, along with the presence of populations of nomadic people who doubtless cross these borders, occurrence of yellow fever cases here would be of significant concern. One hopes that the vaccination campaign proceeds swiftly and no new cases occur in this part of Central Darfur. It would be of interest to know if YF virus mosquito vectors are present here.

A map showing the location of Central Darfur can be accessed at http://www.maplandia.com/sudan/darfur/ and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at http://healthmap.org/r/4Iun . - Mod.TY]
